## 1. Operational Context & Mission Scope
Following the catastrophic landfall and subsequent flooding caused by Hurricane Harvey in the Corpus Christi region, local subterranean fiber infrastructure suffered widespread cascading failures. Regional cellular networks were entirely saturated by emergency traffic, suffering from dropped packets and power-depleted towers. The emergency field office required an immediate, high-availability backhaul solution to handle critical data logistics, supply lines, and medical coordination.

During reconnaissance, the local Fixed Wireless ISP, **Gecko Internet**, was identified as the sole functioning commercial internet infrastructure remaining in the area due to their high-altitude line-of-sight tower positioning. The mission required staging a rapid-deployment mast on-site, mounting a directional subscriber antenna, aligning it with the surviving Gecko Internet tower array, and distributing a secured local network (LAN) for disaster relief staff.

---

## 2. Deployment Timeline & Phases

### Phase 1: Site Survey & Mast Rigging (Day 1 - Morning)
* Conducted a physical assessment of the designated relief site to find a high-point structural mounting location with an unobstructed Line of Sight (LoS) toward the nearest standing Gecko Internet sector tower.
* Erected a heavy-duty temporary mast mount on the facility roof, bracing it mechanically to withstand residual high-velocity coastal winds.

### Phase 2: Power Conditioning Setup (Day 1 - Midday)
* Deployed a portable field generator to supply power to the core network stack. 
* Because raw generator output exhibits major voltage sags and frequency fluctuations that can instantly destroy delicate microwave radios, the generator feed was run through an online double-conversion UPS to ensure a continuous, clean 120V AC signal.

### Phase 3: Fixed Wireless Alignment & Link Lock (Day 1 - Afternoon)
* Mounted a high-gain directional subscriber dish onto the rooftop mast and ran outdoor-rated, shielded Cat5e cable down to the temporary server room.
* Manually aligned the dish to the Gecko Internet sector antenna, precision-tuning the azimuth and elevation while tracking RSSI (Received Signal Strength Indicator) and CINR (Carrier-to-Interference-plus-Noise Ratio) until a stable, low-latency symmetric link was locked.

### Phase 4: Core Routing & Traffic Micro-Management (Day 1 - Evening)
* Terminated the Gecko Internet handoff into the WAN port of the site firewall.
* Configured isolated operational VLANs and aggressive Quality of Service (QoS) queues to protect the newly established wireless backhaul from being choked by non-essential background traffic.

